Comment (policies/secretsmanager_admin_principal_present.rego:68):
**Full IAM wildcard `"*"` is not recognized as admin evidence (low).** `admin_actions_normalized` is built from `data.admin_action_set` (`secretsmanager:*`, `secretsmanager:DeleteSecret`, `secretsmanager:PutResourcePolicy`) by literal upper-case match. A resource policy that grants `"Action": "*"` — strictly *broader* than `secretsmanager:*` — produces `upper("*") == "*"`, which is not in the set. So `admin_principal_present` is false for that principal and `admin_principal_missing` fires on a resource policy that is, in fact, over-broad. The remediation guidance ("add an administrative action") then directs the operator the wrong way.

Suggested fix: add `"*"` to the recognized admin-action set (either in-policy as `admin_actions_normalized | {"*"}`, or as an entry in `data.admin_action_set`), and add a test for an Allow principal with `Action: "*"` satisfying `admin_principal_present`. Alternatively, document in `data.json` / README that wildcard recognition is literal-match only.
Implementation guidance: In policies/secretsmanager_confidential_policy_scope.rego, update violation[{"id": "principal_outside_cleared_role_set"}] so wildcard principals are not also reported as outside the cleared role set. Add not principal_is_wildcard(principal) after allow_effect(principal) and before iterating arn := principal_values(principal)[_]. Keep violation[{"id": "wildcard_principal"}] unchanged as the authoritative finding for bare "*" and Principal.AWS wildcard forms.
Implementation guidance: In policies/secretsmanager_privacy_subprocessor_posture.rego, update violation[{"id": "principal_outside_integration_role_set"}] so wildcard principals are not also reported as outside the vendor integration role set. Add not principal_is_wildcard(principal) after allow_effect(principal) and before arn := principal_values(principal)[_]. Keep violation[{"id": "principal_wildcard"}] unchanged as the single finding for wildcard principals.
Implementation guidance: Prevent missing account.account_id from producing false cross-account findings. In policies/secretsmanager_resource_policy_least_privilege.rego, add account_id != "" to violation[{"id": "cross_account_principal_undocumented"}] before comparing principal_account != account_id. Apply the same guard to the cross-account/cross-border rules that depend on the local account id: violation[{"id": "cross_account_principal"}] in policies/secretsmanager_confidential_policy_scope.rego, violation[{"id": "vendor_principal_cross_account_undocumented"}] in policies/secretsmanager_vendor_credential_policy_scope.rego, and the account-id fallback violation[{"id": "cross_border_principal_undocumented"}] in policies/secretsmanager_privacy_transfer_governance.rego. Do not gate wildcard, excess-action, KMS, rotation, tag, or documented-role checks; only suppress findings whose correctness depends on knowing the resource account id. If tests exist for these policies, add a focused case showing a missing account.account_id does not emit the cross-account finding.
Implementation guidance: In policies/secretsmanager_admin_principal_present.rego, treat IAM Action "*" as administrative evidence because it is broader than secretsmanager:*. Update admin_actions_normalized to include "*" in addition to upper-cased entries from data.admin_action_set, for example by unioning the configured set with {"*"}; alternatively add "*" to the default admin_action_set in policies/data.json, but the in-policy union is safer because wildcard admin remains recognized even if deployments customize data.admin_action_set. Add or update a test in policies/secretsmanager_admin_principal_present_test.rego with an Allow principal whose action is "*" and assert that admin_principal_missing is not emitted. Preserve allow_effect filtering so Deny "*" does not satisfy admin_principal_present.
